liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: US President Joe Biden has arrived in Hawaii, where wildfires have left a trail of devastation. He and First Lady Jill Biden are meeting with first responders and receiving updates from state and local officials. They will then visit the devastated city of Lahaina to see the wildfire damage firsthand, talk with survivors, receive a briefing from state and local officials and deliver remarks. Mr Biden is also expected to pay tribute to the victims. The fires have killed more than 100 people in Hawaii.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The clean-up has begun in some areas of California from Storm Hilary and it now moves to Nevada, Utah and into the north-west of the US. In Cathedral city, locals were forced to flee their homes in the middle of the night as large downpours led to flash flooding. Some residents of a care home had to be rescued with excavation equipment. Reuters is reporting the storm flooded streets and downed power lines across Southern California but no deaths have been recorded.

title.children: BHP profits down 37pc, Coles profits up 4.8pc, ASX down in early trade

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Coles Group has reported its profits for 2023. It's posted a 4.8% increase in full-year profit, to $1.09 billion. Its financial results: Net profit after tax: up 4.8%, to $1.09 billion Sales revenue: up 5.9% to $40.5 billion EBITDA: up 3.8% to $3.38 billion Interim dividend per share: 36 cents Final dividend per share: 30 cents Total dividend per share: 66 cents James Graham, Coles Group chairman: "It is pleasing to record continuing sales growth and broadly stable after-tax profits from continuing operations in another year market by challenging operations. "The payment of a steady final dividend of 30 cents per share is in line with our 80 to 90 per cent full year dividend payout policy." The company achieve fourth-quarter sales growth of 8% in supermarkets and 2.9% in liquor.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Coles profits up 4.8% to $1.09 billion

children.content: Coles Group has reported its profits for 2023.
Net profit after tax: up 4.8%, to $1.09 billion
"It is pleasing to record continuing sales growth and broadly stable after-tax profits from continuing operations in another year market by challenging operations.
"The payment of a steady final dividend of 30 cents per share is in line with our 80 to 90 per cent full year dividend payout policy."
The company achieve fourth-quarter sales growth of 8% in supermarkets and 2.9% in liquor.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: BHP has set aside the first paragraph of its profit results to note the deaths of two colleagues during the year. It's a tragic reminder that nobody should be dying at work or suffering serious injuries. Its full-year 2023 results: Full-year underlying profit: down 37% to $US13.4 billion Attributable profit after tax from total operations: down 58% to US$12.9 billion Revenue: down 17% to $US53.8 billion Underlying EBITDA: $US28 billion (-31%) The mining giant says its revenue decreased primarily as a result of significantly lower prices for iron ore, metallurgical coal, and copper. It says while it increased copper, iron ore and nickel sales volumes, and exchange rates were favourable, its profit from operations and EBITDA declined primarily due to lower commodity prices and the impacts of inflation on its cost base, particularly on labour, diesel and electricity prices. BHP shareholders will receive a full-year dividend of $US1.70 per share. The profit results were slightly weaker than analysts expected.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: BHP profits down 37% on lower commodity prices
